SIMPLE: prog
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prog
<hw>Prog</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Progged</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>. <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Progging</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. D.
<ets>prachen</ets>, G. <ets>prachern</ets>, Dan. <ets>prakke</ets>, Sw.
<ets>pracka</ets>, to beg, L. <ets>procare</ets>, <ets>procari</ets>, to
ask, demand, and E. <ets>prowl</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To wander
about and beg; to seek food or other supplies by low arts; to seek for
advantage by mean shift or tricks.</def> <mark>[Low]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A perfect artist in <qex>progging</qex> for money.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have been endeavoring to <qex>prog</qex> for you.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To steal; to rob; to filch.</def> <mark>[Low]</mark>
<rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To prick; to goad; to progue.</def>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prog</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Prog
<hw>Prog</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Victuals got by begging,
or vagrancy; victuals of any kind; food; supplies.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So long as he picked from the filth his <qex>prog</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>R. Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A vagrant beggar; a tramp.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A goal; progue.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Progenerate</ent>⟦br⟧
